An l-f-c-s preparation checklist.

Before you book the exam, it is worth running yourself through an honest self-check. The standard to aim for is this: you should be able to do each of the following from a blank prompt, in under five minutes, with no notes. Let me walk through the categories so you can test yourself against them.

On the essentials: can you navigate the filesystem and use find, grep, sed, and awk for ad-hoc queries; write both a for loop and a while-read loop; produce a basic script with the production preamble; and create and extract archives in the common compression formats? On permissions and users: can you create a user with a home directory, set a password, and add them to a group; configure the sudoers file safely for a specific user; set the special permission bits correctly; and use the access-control-list tools?

On storage, which carries heavy weight: can you partition a new disk with a modern partition table; make both e-x-t-four and x-f-s filesystems; mount permanently through the filesystem table using a u-u-i-d; configure a swap file; build l-v-m from scratch all the way from physical volume to mounted filesystem; grow a volume together with its filesystem; and take and remove a snapshot? On services and boot: can you write a service unit and a timer unit from scratch, create a drop-in override, query the journal by unit, time, priority, and boot, and configure a cron job? On networking: can you set a static address, configure dee-en-ess, set up key-based s-s-h login, harden the s-s-h server, open specific firewall ports, and diagnose with the standard tools? And finally, on packages and on logs and monitoring: can you install, remove, and search software, add a third-party repository, and read the logs to find what changed? Any item you cannot do smoothly is simply your next practice session. Turn the gaps into hands-on drills, and when the list is all green, you are ready.
